section.subsection:
            Basis Vectors and Unit Vectors

Every vector in \RR^{3} can be written using three components: \vv{x} = \dotprod{x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}}. Each component corresponds to a coordinate axis, and we can rewrite \vv{x} as a linear combination of three different vectors, with each vector corresponding to a coordinate axis:
            \vv{x} = x_{1}\dotprod{1,0,0}+x_{2}\dotprod{0,1,0}+x_{3}\dotprod{0,0,1}.
            These vectors are important enough that we'll give them a name: the standard basis vectors.

                Standard Basis Vectors
                vectorsstandard basis


The standard basis for \RR^{3} is the set \{\vv{i},\vv{j},\vv{k}\}, where
                    \vv{i} = \dotprod{1,0,0},\quad\vv{j} = \dotprod{0,1,0}\quad\text{and}\quad\vv{k} = \dotprod{0,0,1}.



As we've seen, every vector \vv{x} in \RR^{3} can be expressed using only these three vectors. The standard basis has two important properties: it is perpendicular (also called orthogonal) and every vector in the collection has magnitude 1. In other words,
            \|\vv{i}\| = \|\vv{j}\| = \|\vv{k}\| = 1.

These vectors are essentially designed to capture the "coordinate directions", and are plotted below.



                        \begin{tikzpicture} [axis/.style={->,blue,thick}, 
